post_text:
Primary School Reminders:

Reminder for (K-2) Parents: September 8th (Tuesday) - Parents and students are asked to come to the Primary School to pick up their Chromebooks and chargers and to meet their teacher between 3:30-5:00pm. Meeting the teachers will happen at classroom windows. Signs will be up to help direct families to the correct classroom window. Cohort B will begin on Thursday September 10th and Cohort A will begin in person on Monday September 14th.

Parents of 3PK and 4PK students: Your child's Chromebook will be picked up on Thursday, September 10th or Friday, September 11th during your child's scheduled window orientation time. 3PK and 4PK students will only come to school for their Orientation session that will be held through the classroom window. Classes will begin for 3PK & 4PK students on Monday September 14th for Cohort A and Thursday September 17th for Cohort B. Please contact your child's teacher with any questions or concerns. The teachers are excited to meet you and your child!

2020 DHS Graduation Updates

There is a mandatory rehearsal for all seniors tomorrow at Ralph Clements field at 9:00am tomorrow (Friday, 7/24). Please plan on two hours.

Parking passes will be distributed to seniors for their families at rehearsal. Gates will open for families at 6:30pm. Please remind your parents to bring their parking pass with them tomorrow.

We will post a link to the live stream on Facebook tomorrow around 6:30pm.

The weather for tomorrow looks great and we are excited to see DHS seniors walk across the stage tomorrow night!

post_text: As we enter this Memorial Day weekend, absent our traditional means of honoring our fallen heroes in arms, please take a moment to give thanks for their sacrifice. There‚Äôs an old saying, ‚ÄúOur rural communities feed, fuel and fight for America.‚Äù It‚Äôs a fact that rural America makes up the greatest proportion of our military. The soldiers that gave their lives to preserve our nation were fighting for a way of life that we love. Community. Caring for neighbors. Supporting our kids. That‚Äôs rural New York and the America these courageous heroes gave their all for. Let‚Äôs take a moment to give them the honor they richly deserve. Socially distanced or not, we owe them everything.

post_text:
The Bacon Baker

Over the last few weeks, DHS freshman Maggie Bacon has started baking desserts. She is taking donations for the goodies and plans to donate the money towards the DCSD backpack program. Maggie is planning to donate $500! For Mother‚Äôs Day, she prepared and delivered 16 items!

Maggie says, "During this craziness of the COVID-19 quarantine we are all in, I have discovered a love of baking. Baking has given me an outlet to showcase my creativity and quite frankly has become very therapeutic. I have even started an Instagram Account called the.bacon.baker....feel free to follow!! I have gotten many followers and people are putting in requests for items and they want to pay me. My original intent was not to make money, so I would like to find a way to help others by donating the profits to those in need. As a proud Dansville Mustang, I have seen how the district has gone above and beyond to support the students and I would like to follow that example."

#DansvilleMustangProud

post_text: Dansville High School and Mr. Terry's Applications of Programming course is proud to announce that they have partnered with Amazon's Future Engineers Scholarship to implement Intro to Computer Science- Python this coming Fall. Industry professionals note that Python is one of the most widely-used programming languages and the best baseline language for learners to master. Dramatically expanding access to computer science is a goal of the ever-evolving tech world, and Dansville is doing its part to prepare students to compete and achieve in the postsecondary world.

Livingston County, New York
April 22 at 9:22 AM ¬∑

CONGRATULATIONS! The Livingston County Board of Supervisors and Youth Bureau are pleased to announce the winners of the 2020 Teen Recognition Awards.

These awards are earned by high school teens as young as 15 who are committed to community improvement, demonstrate leadership, or are a role model to others because they have overcome personal challenges. These are the youth in our community who subtly go about making the world around them a little more special by their actions and attitudes. Since 1995, over 1,800 youth have been recognized.

Relationships are the cornerstone of positive youth development; therefore, this recognition is not possible without the support of the nominators. Nominators come from a variety of places: schools, churches, neighborhoods, civic organizations and clubs. We appreciate the time they took to notice the good in these youth. https://bit.ly/3bvYU8D
text:
Livingston County, New York
April 22 at 9:22 AM ¬∑

CONGRATULATIONS! The Livingston County Board of Supervisors and Youth Bureau are pleased to announce the winners of the 2020 Teen Recognition Awards.

These awards are earned by high school teens as young as 15 who are committed to community improvement, demonstrate leadership, or are a role model to others because they have overcome personal challenges. These are the youth in our community who subtly go about making the world around them a little more special by their actions and attitudes. Since 1995, over 1,800 youth have been recognized.

Relationships are the cornerstone of positive youth development; therefore, this recognition is not possible without the support of the nominators. Nominators come from a variety of places: schools, churches, neighborhoods, civic organizations and clubs. We appreciate the time they took to notice the good in these youth. https://bit.ly/3bvYU8D

post_text:
Check out this image. Just a bowl of fruit, right? Try looking at it upside down... do you see the new image?

This piece is by Arcimboldo, a Mannerist artist from the 1500's. He would take fruits, vegetables, fish, books, and other objects, then paint them to look like a person. Several of his artworks, like the one here, can be flipped upside down so that the face is hidden!

Check out the Art Link of the Day: Arcimboldo Art Creator
https://mustangartresources.weebly.com/digital-art.html
This web application that lets you create portraits out of produce - just like Arcimboldo!

Let's see your crazy creations! Screenshot your creation, send it to pullenk@dansvillecsd.org and we will post your work in our online gallery: https://mustangartresources.weebly.com/your-art.html

post_text:
The Girls Track & Field team is working hard to stay in shape and get ready for the rest of the season. It‚Äôs hard not knowing when we will be getting to practice together as a team but in the meantime, we are making the most of it. The Lady Mustangs have daily workouts posted in our Google Classroom by Coach McMaster & Coach DeBell, nutrition & recipes being shared weekly, guest one-day workout planners, this week Jasmyn Fox and photo challenges. We also have a Snapchat challenge group being run by five seniors - Emma Beardsley, Jasmyn Fox, Maddie Jacobs, Jessie Qiu & Maddie Shafer. Plus we have the added bonus of continuing of Strength Training with Coach Pogel.

Coach McMaster & Coach DeBell are extremely proud of how hard the girls continue to work and we look forward to competing later in the season.

Go Mustangs!

5th grade chorus students: Tuesdays at 3pm and Thursdays at 5pm.

Last week, around 40 students took advantage of our first session. Any questions, please reach out to Mrs. Reynolds.

Do not visit the school if you:

Show symptoms of COVID-19 (fever, cough, achiness, fatigue, and/or shortness of breath) or have been diagnosed.

Recently traveled overseas or knowingly came in direct contact with anyone who has recently traveled overseas.

Have been directed to be quarantined.

Call the school if you need help arranging a pick up.

Primary School Home Instructional Materials Pick Up

Hello Primary School Families,

On Wednesday, March 18th, you will be permitted to come to the Primary School Bus Loop between the hours of 8:00am to 3:00pm to pick up prepared grade-level instructional packets for your child(ren). Teachers have been working hard putting together materials that will be essential to maintaining learning during this extended school closing.

Teachers will have packets ready for pick up in the Primary School Bus Loop. Each packet will be organized by grade level and have children‚Äôs names on them. If families need something from the classroom, one of our staff will be happy to retrieve it from the classroom for you. We are only distributing materials at the designated areas at the Primary School Bus Loop.

If you have any questions or need to make other arrangements please call the Primary School Main Office at 335-4040 x. 2004.

Thank you all for your patience and understanding as we work through this challenging time.

post_text:
Cold & Flu Season Continues!

Please advise children and young people to:

Wash hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds.

Avoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth with unwashed hands.

Avoid close contact with people who are sick.

Stay home when you are sick.

Cover your mouth and nose with a tissue or your sleeve (not your hands) when coughing or sneezing. If you use a tissue, throw it in the trash.

Please remember to:

Use an alcohol based hand sanitizer that contains at least 60% alcohol if soap and water are not available.

Routinely clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces.

Thank you!

post_text: Are you reading this from a computer? Your iPhone? This likely would not be possible without the creation of lenses! Thanks to the help from individuals like Jim VanKouwenberg from Optimax and Jason Brightful from Monroe Community College, this post is possible. Today's Lunch and Learn allowed students to eat lunch while learning about apprenticeships available in the optics field, training available at MCC, and the importance of career exploration! We look forward to our next Lunch and Learn on Tuesday, March 31st. Stay tuned to find out who will be presenting!

Rochester National College Fair Field Trip ‚Äì March 16, 2020

The High School Counselors and Honors Academy Advisers are excited to be sponsoring a field trip to the National College Fair in Rochester! This trip is open to all members of the junior class and to sophomores in the Honors Academy. Attending the College Fair will be a wonderful way for you to get information about many different colleges and to talk with admissions officers. There will be almost 200 colleges from around the country represented there, so being prepared will help you make the best use of your time.

We will only have one bus going, so the first 40 students who turn their completed packet (all three items on the checklist below) back into the Counseling Office will be the ones able to join us. Please see Mr. Kastner if you have any questions, or if you need help getting the required information.

1. ‚ÄúPermission To Miss Class‚Äù form

2. Pre-registration bar code

3. List of 5 colleges
